    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-29T09:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-29T09:00:00-05:00" n="72"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/834: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Finland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Helsinki</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-29T16:00:00+02:00"
                            >August 29, 1941—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 29—2:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>389. With reference to a report which I understand appeared recently in the <hi
                        rend="italic">New York Post</hi> and perhaps in other American newspapers
                        <pb facs="0072" n="60" xml:id="pg_60"/> to the effect that direct
                    negotiations between Finland and the Soviet Union for an armistice were
                    contemplated, I learn from Secretary General of Foreign Office that nothing is
                    known here of any such negotiations. He is inclined to think that this report
                    may be related to a recent Russian broadcast in which it is reported to have
                    been said that Finland would be well-advised to consider such a step.</p>
                <p>Any such report should in my opinion be judged in the light of Finnish
                    Government’s consistent statements beginning with President Ryti’s radio address
                    June 26 that Finland’s objectives in present hostilities are limited, and in the
                    light of the fact that this Government’s freedom of action will largely depend
                    upon the attitude of its German co-belligerent.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schoenfeld</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
